                         **Risk and Return of stock investments**

This project analyses the historical risk and return of 6 stocks from public companies during a period of 1 year, commencing January 2022.

Stocks are an investment product that give the stockholder a share in the ownership of the companies issuing the stocks. Investors buy stocks with the aim of increasing their capital through: a) an increase in the price of the stocks they have bought and/or b) receipt of payments (dividends) from earnings of the companies for which they hold stocks.

Like so many other products and services, stock prices are driven by supply and demand. Some of the factors that can affect the supply - demand dynamics of stocks include: company issues, state of the economy, national and international politics. As stock prices move up as well as down, there is no guarantee that a company's stock price will grow and that a company will pay a dividend. At times stock prices can drop significantly, say by more than 10%, over a short period causing some impatient investors to sell their stocks and thus incurr losses. Companies can also fail, it is therefore possible that an investor can lose all the money invested in stocks.

Each investment product, such as cash, stocks, bonds etc has its own level Risk and Return features. The relationship between Risk and Return on an investment is that investors taking on greater risk will seek greater potential reward. Similarily, the lower the risk, lower is the potential return. For example, an investor can invest in shares of start_up company (high risk) and lose everything or make a fortune (high reward). Alternatively, investing in an established company with a track record of steady growth (low risk) an investor is unlikely to loose all his money but is also less likely to make a fortune. Therefore, investing requires individuals to take on certain amount of risk depending on their financial goals and risk appitite. Historically, investors have gained significant capital growth by investing in stocks. This has only been achieved by investing with patience and over a long term. Investing over longer term allow stock markets to recover temporary losses and deliver positve returns.

From above, we have a columns with a multilevel (2 level) header consisting of an inner and an outer level. The inner level identifies the ticker symbols and the outter level shows the Adj Close, Close, Open etc price of the stocks. Two "Close" prices are shown. The Close price is the last traing price of the day and Adj Close price is the price after dividend payouts, issue of additional shares and stock splits have been taken into account. Adj Close price is a thus a better parameter for stock returns than the Close price. It should be noted that the first record occurs on 2022-01-03, which is the first trading day of the year and not the start date specified in the download request.

correlation Lets examine our stocks returns further to see if there is some relationship between these stock returns by creating a correlation matrix and then visualising this as a heatmap.

In a correlation matrix cell values have a range of -1 to +1. Values near 0 means there is no linear trend between two stocks returns, such as XOM and JNJ. Two stock returns that have a cell value greater than 0 indicate that they are positvely correlated ie as one stock return increases so does the other. The closer a cell value is to 1, the stronger the relationship between the stocks. A correlation of 1, along the diagonal, means each stock return is correlating with itself (perfect correlation ie moving in the same direction with the same magnitude). In negative correlations (negative cell values), as one stock return increases the other stock return decreases, and vice versa. When a correlation matrix contains a lot of numerical data it can be difficult and time consuming to see relationships and general trends between variables, eg stocks returns. Graphical representations such as Heatmaps (see below) are utilised to overcome these issues.

In [72]:
# heatmap of the ret correlation matrix

plt.figure(figsize = (10,6))
sns.heatmap(ret.corr(), cmap = "Reds", annot = True, vmax = 0.8)
plt.show()

It is much easier to visualise and analyse data in the form of a heatmap than a numerical correlation matrix. Darker the cell colour greater the correlation between a pair of stocks and vise versa. Highest positive correlation (0.7, dark red coloured cells) occurs between AAL and BA. Light colour cells indicate low positive correlation as in the case of : a) XOM and each of the other stocks ie these stocks appear to be indepenedent of from XOM. b) JNJ and each of the other stocks ie these stocks appear to be indepenedent of from JNJ.

Negative or low correlation between a pair of stocks reduces risk because as the price of one stock falls it may be compensated by a rise in the price of the other (-ve correction) or at least a lesser drop. In this way investors aim to achieve better returns with an acceptable level of risk.
